comment.author: 34001651@N00
comment._content:
[http://www.flickr.com/photos/8793648@N06] 

No, you're quite wrong. Those old hand-knitted woollen ladies' swimming cozzies looked extremely flattering when wet, especially around the flange region, where they tended to gather into a sodden clump, that attracted the eye most effectively. Then there was the interesting smell that the wet wool mixed with promiscuous Aussie sheila's perspiration emitted of course - reminiscent of a female dingo on heat. 

And naturally the one-time popularity of these garments went a considerable way in supporting the Australian wool industry so vital to the nation's economy then --- this being long before the Chinese bought up 75% of Australia, to dig out 100% of the country's mineral wealth, leaving nothing but gigantic holes in the barren Australian landscape, where the herds of filthy, starving sheep used to graze.
